{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f1670481-765c-4cf1-bf3c-ff7af900b58a","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can give you the exact configuration needed. To publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool**, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n1. **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a dotnet tool (must be a console app / `Exe`).\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n3. **Pack & publish:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet pack -c Release\n   dotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n     --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n   ```\n4. **Users install with:**\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\n   ```\n\nThen they can reference it in their MCP client config pointing to the `my-mcp-server` command with stdio transport. Make sure your `OutputType` is `Exe` and the entry point reads from stdin/writes to stdout.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f7de434b-91bc-4019-bf97-0bb2685add72","outputTokens":425,"requestId":"842D:3D4537:1157917:156AD4B:69FFDBA8"},"id":"e5198e60-51e7-4de6-b259-2bc9905ab9a4","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:13:20.796Z","parentId":"9e4d4df6-f84a-4052-b062-2d01770d9825"}
